        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The technical justification is based on mock simulations using the CASA simulator whose chosen input model was described in the scientific justification section.

We simulate our Sunyaev-Zel'dovich models for different mean post-shock temperatures, ranging from 25-44keV using ALMA C34-1 and ACA cycle 2 configurations, giving angular resolutions of 4.3'' (ALMA) and 18.5'' (ACA) respectively at a central frequency of 100 GHz, 15 GHz total bandwidth and single pointing for 3 hrs (ALMA) and 6 hrs (ACA) on-source integration time respectively.

For the spectral set-up, we ask for Band 3 observations at an LO1 frequency of 100 GHz, using the largest 1.875 GHz bandwidth per baseband as the Sunyaev-Zel'dovich spectral signature is known and we require continuum observations.
The configurations were chosen such that the shock width of 36’’ is covered at 4’’ resolution, which allows for the tip of the bow shock arc to be imaged (Fig.7) together with APEX-SZ data (1-6').
The chosen observation times and their associated 100 GHz sensitivities of 8e-6Jy (ALMA) and 6.5e-5Jy (ACA) were chosen such that the relevant mean post-shock electron temperature ranges (25-44 keV) can be probed with ALMA at sufficient significance (Fig.7), which is motivated by the need for a required margin given the geometric assumptions and uncertainties in the de-projected density model by Markevitch et al.(2002). 
In estimating the SNR across the shock front, we average the SZ signal in the cleaned simulated ALMA/ACA feathered map over the post and pre-shock regions within the 41'' maximum recoverable region. We find that, for the chosen instrumental set-up, the projected SZ discontinuity can be imaged to a SNR of 8 and 15 for the 25 and 44keV mean post-shock temperatures respectively (Fig. 7b,c).
The averaged signal (Fig. 7d) over a horizontal slab across the shock front (box in Fig. 7a using 10'' RA binning intervals) of the feathered noisy ALMA/ACA cleaned images (Fig. 7b,c) illustrates the feasibility of feathered ALMA/ACA observations to distinguish different post-shock temperatures for a given geometric shock model from the projected SZ discontinuity. 

In order to stress ALMA/ACA’s ability to map the projected pressure bow shock geometry up to 41’’ scales, Markevitch’s model was compared to a ‘small shock’ model which is characterized by a 20’’, rather than a 36’’, de-projected cold front/shock front distance, giving rise to a bow shock pressure arc with a smaller curvature radius. By comparing the cleaned feathered noisy ALMA/ACA maps of Markevitch’s model (Fig. 7b,c) with the ‘small shock model’ (Fig. 7e,f), it is clear that different bow shock geometries can indeed be distinguished using the proposed observational set-up of a single pointing study including the ACA.

One factor which may limit the detection of the Sunyaev-Zel’dovich signal is the presence of point sources which may ‘fill in’ the SZ decrement.  Rex et al. (2010) and Johansson et al. (2010) investigated the point source SEDs behind the bullet cluster. The sources that lie within 1’-3’ of the shock front (Rex et al 2010) are HLS10, HLS11 and HLS16 with 100 GHz fluxes of 16.7±1.4mJy, 7.4±1.1mJy and 25.3 ±1.3 mJy. These can however be modeled and removed in the visibility plane. In addition, radio halos may also come into play at the shock front where electrons are accelerated. The radio halo in the Bullet cluster has been studied by Liang et al. (2000) and they derived a spectral index of -1.2 which suggests that at 100 GHz, this effect is negligible.

The simulations in Fig. 7 take into account the estimated noise level from the ALMA Sensitivity calculator, thus supporting our choices for the configuration, time/sensitivity, pointing and correlator set-up.

We therefore ask for a total observation time of 14.87 hours (with overheads) with 3h ALMA and 6h on-source ACA integration times for ALMA cycle 2 to reach a sensitivity of 8e-6Jy/beam for the ALMA array.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
